Jan 12 2005	Okay but you might do better...	We stayed at the Europa House Hotel in Sussex Gardens (wonderful location about a block from Paddington train/underground station and Heathrow Express) for 5 nights in November 2004 and paid 60 pounds ($111) a night for a double room--good mattress, reading lights over the bed, in-room coffee/tea--with a small bathroom. The shower was tiny, about 24 inches wide, and the unavoidable wet shower curtain that billowed in on the bather made it very much like showering inside a wet T-shirt. The bathroom vent did not work. That aside, the room was clean and quiet, although the decor was decidedly tired and dreary. It could be chilly at times because the central heat was turned on at 5:30 p.m. and turned off in the morning. Our room was on the ground floor, in the back, as I had requested when I reserved online. Management was responsive to questions and requests and let us check in as soon as we arrived, about 10:30 a.m., which was much appreciated after a long flight. TV reception was awful--no satellite or visible antenna--so no CNN and only three viewable channels of mainly trash TV (little news). The breakfast was basic but adequate: fried eggs, frozen juice, frozen hash browns, canned baked beans, tea/coffee, and toast. Boring long before the fifth morning, but enough food to keep us going for hours. Main complaint: breakfast was rushed, only served from 8-9 a.m., unlike other B&amp;B's I've stayed in that generally have a wider window of serving times or slightly longer hours on Sundays. There were many similar hotels lining the street, and I think I might have done better pricewise if I had shopped around. Europa House was full on just one of the weekend nights; otherwise, there were always vacancies there and in the other hotels along Sussex Gardens, at least in the off-season. While the hotel is nothing special, it's reliable, functional, and convenient. I'd stay there again.	
